  "steps": [
    {
      "title": "1",
      "body": "Cut the box for the nightstand to size. Bevel the edges with either a track saw or a table saw.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/8555012a73279ab6.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "2",
      "body": "Glue up the box with wood glue and clamps. Let dry overnight.\nTip: corner clamps work really well for this!",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/07325f6f60b01850.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "3",
      "body": "Drill 1/4\" holes about 1.5\" away from the edges of the front and back of the box on both the top and bottom. The holes should be 1\" deep. Tip: wrap a piece of painters tape 1\" down on your drill bit to make the right depth hole.\nAdd a little glue to the holes then pound in a 1/4\" round dowel until it hits the back of the holes.\nCut the dowel flush with the nightstand with a hand saw.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/16c6250fd3e6fd14.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "4",
      "body": "Cut the mitered legs to size. This will be the front of the base.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/6da1c8b531ef8388.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "5",
      "body": "Drill pocket holes on the top and bottom piece for the mitered legs. This will give the pocket screw enough material to grab onto for a strong hold.\nUse wood glue and 1.5\" pocket screws to put the mitered legs together.\nIt helps to use clamps here!",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/238dc44063d1bbdd.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "4",
      "body": "Cut the pieces to size for the back legs.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/dad4bdeb601ca5ea.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "5",
      "body": "Drill pocket holes in the top and bottom piece, making sure they face up.\nUse wood glue and 1.5\" pocket screws attach the back legs together.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/a1f5fe235a1ab2f8.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "6",
      "body": "Drill pocket holes into the side pieces for the base, making sure they face the bottom.\nThis allows the pocket screws to have enough hold when they screw into the mitered legs.\nUse wood glue and 1.5\" pocket screws to screw the side pieces to the mitered legs and the back legs.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/378f4b05013d4951.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "7",
      "body": "Using figure 8 fasteners and a forstner bit that is slightly larger than the figure 8's, drill 2 holes on each side of the top of the base until the figure 8's sit flush inside.\nScrew the figure 8's in and then screw in the top of the nightstand to the base.\nThe base of the nightstand should be flush on all sides with the top of the nightstand.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/201291c66770cb7a.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "8",
      "body": "Time to build the drawers!\nCut the drawer pieces to size. Run 1/4\" groove on the inside bottom of all the drawer pieces except for the bottom. You can use a table saw for this or a track saw.\nDrill pocket holes in just the front and back pieces of the drawers.\nTest fit the plywood bottom to make sure it slides easily into the grooves when the drawer box is all together.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/5f96b40c0b4c9d4d.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "9",
      "body": "Use wood glue and 1.25\" pocket screws to put the drawer together.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/81648decee312cf8.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "10",
      "body": "Install the drawer slides so they are offset .75\" from the front of the nightstand.\nThe bottom drawer slide should be installed about 1.75\" up from the bottom of the nightstand and the second drawer slide should be installed 2\" up from the first drawer slide.\nTip: cut a scrap piece of wood to the size of the drawer slide spacing, put the drawer slide on top and screw it in. Perfectly level drawer slides!\nThe drawer slides should be in the center of the drawers.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/2edbf876264ced60.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "11",
      "body": "For the drawer fronts, if you want to make those 5 grooves I suggest using a table saw or a track saw.\nEvenly space the 5 grooves on the drawer fronts. Cut the grooves just once, the width of the blade you are using will be the perfect width. Make sure the grooves go in about 1/4\".\nThen attach the drawer fronts using clamps and 1.25\" screws from the inside of the drawer.\nMake sure you have an even gap around all 4 sides of both drawers. There should be about 1/16\" to 1/8\" gap.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/97bb3834f3d1aabe.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "12",
      "body": "Route a 1/4\" x 1/4\" rabbet on the backside of the nightstand.\nCut the plywood back to size and nail the back onto the rabbet.",
      "image": "https://pub-b845b7e7b4924e4d8f2520661b54734d.r2.dev/plans/736f07f472b7e9c3.webp"
    },
    {
      "title": "13",
      "body": "Sand, stain and install your favorite hardware and you've made yourself a nightstand!"
    }
  ],
